Although the mechanosensation might be the earliest among all the senses (

), the molecular properties of some mechanosensitive ion channels and their related structures is yet to be determined. A substantial amount of information has been reported for mechanosensitive channels (

); however, the absence of appropriate preparations to perform experiments at the cell level, difficulty in generation and application of a calibrated mechanical stimulus, polymorphic nature of the mechanosensation, and a limited number of specific pharmacological agents make the functional characterization of novel mechanosensitive ion channels difficult. The presence of a mechanosensitive channel has been reported in various functional studies in crayfishes (

; 

). There is no information, however, on the genetic and molecular properties of such mechanosensitive channels in the crayfish. A set of mechanically activated channels have been reported in prokaryotes (

). Recent improvements in the field have been achieved and for the first time a eukaryotic ion channel has been shown to be mechanosensitive (

). The discovered Piezo channels fulfill all the criteria defined for a mechanosensitive ion channel (

). The mechanical force, developing in the lipid bilayer membrane, specifically drives the channel into an open state (

). Piezo channels are specifically gated by the force from the lipid bilayer and they are the representative example of a distinct group of mechanosensitive channels. It has been reported that some other 
type
of mechanosensitive channels require additional functional or structural elements for opening, as in the mechanosensor of 

Drosophila

and the vertebrate hair cells (

; 

; 

). Protocadherin and cadherin (

), transmembrane channel (TMC)-like protein (

; 

), LHFPL5 (

), and TMIE (

) constitute a mechano-electrical transducer (MET) complex generating the primary mechanotransduction in the hair cells. An alternative gating mechanism, driven by the force from the filament has been proposed (

). Although there are some opposing reports, TMC has been proposed as a candidate mechanosensitive ion channel based on gene silencing and structural analysis studies (

; 

; 

). It has been proposed that an MET complex is necessary for mechanosensitivity in hair cells; however, TMC has been reported to independently function for salt chemosensation in the nematode C 
aenorhabditis

elegans
(

Chatzigeorgiou 
et al.,
2013

)

. Expression of TMC in heterologous cells may retain such a function. TMC genes have been reported in many species such as 

C. elegans

as well as in mammals. In crustaceans, however, out of a few genome drafts not much information is yet available for the genetic and structural properties of the TMC genes and related proteins (

). We present 
de novo
cloning and structural study of a TMC-like gene and its related protein in the crayfish 

Astacus leptodactylus
(
Eschscholtz, 1823
)

.

TMC mRNA sequences from neighboring species were aligned to previously assembled transcriptome drafts (

). Primers were designed in reference to the transcript sequence with the highest alignment score (

). PCR experiments were conducted to amplify a gene fragment and the obtained product was sequenced for confirmation. Two pairs of nesting primers were designed for a pair of rapid amplification of cDNA ends polymerase chain reaction (RACE) in both directions. We used a commercially available kit (SMARTer 5 
ʹ
/3 
ʹ
kit; Clontech, Mountain View, CA, 
USA
) for the RACE experiments. PCR products were run on gel electrophoresis for evaluation and selected samples were purified by using a kit (QIAquick; Qiagen, Hilden, 
Germany
). Purified products were sequenced either in a Sanger sequencing or NGS platform (Illumina, San Diego, CA, 
USA
).

We calculated the structure of the cloned channel protein by using different approaches. Firstly, the protein sequence was submitted to I-TASSER platform for calculation of the three-dimensional structure (

); I-TASSER platform used the mouse TMEM16A chloride-channel crystallographic structure as the template (

). An alternative calculation, with some success, was performed in AlphaFold platform (

; 

). The best result was obtained in SWISS-MODEL, which is another platform for the structural calculations (

). The platform used the recently published 

C. elegans

tmc-1 single particle cryoelectron microscopy data as the template for calculations (

). Figures of the structural calculations were produced in Visual Molecular Dynamics (VMD) platform (

).

Primers were designed in reference to the previously prepared ganglionic transcriptome draft. Different combinations of the primers resulted in various sizes of gene fragments in PCR experiments. ‘F1_tmc1’ and ‘R1_tmc1’ primers gave products with an approximately 350 base-pairs in size (
Fig. 1A
). Combination of ‘F2_tmc1’ and ‘R1_tmc1’ primers produced a PCR product in size of ~1,000 base pairs (not shown).

The gene fragments were Sanger sequenced. Analysis of the sequence of the translated gene fragments revealed a sequence similar to that of the conserved domain of ‘transmembrane channel like protein’ (

). The identified sequence was used to design new primers to explore the missing parts of the mRNA. ‘F3_tmc1’ and ‘R1_tmc1’ resulted in ~1.6 kbp-long PCR product. This product was sequenced in an NGS platform (Illumina, San Diego, CA, 
USA
). Short reads were 
de novo
assembled into a set of contigs in DNASTAR platform (SeqMan NGen®, Version 17.2; DNASTAR, Madison, WI, 
USA
). The calculated contigs were assembled to the identified gene fragment. The newly assembled sequence (1.6 kbp in size) was used to design the primers ‘tmc_3F’ and ‘tmc_5R’ for the subsequent rapid amplification of cDNA ends, polymerase chain reactions (RACE-PCR) (
Table 1
).

The ORF was translated into a protein sequence of 832 amino acids (GenBank accession number WCO13212). The identified amino acid sequence was compared to a collection of 29 sequences available in several other species. MATLAB environment was used to generate a phylogenetic tree with the Jukes-Cantor distance calculation method. A distinction between TMC1, TMC2, and TMC7 channels was apparent in a graph (
Fig. 2A
). The calculations show a similarity to TMC7 group of channels for the cloned protein. The protein sequence was aligned against the human TMC proteins and an apparent similarity was observed. especially to human TMC7 protein. (
Fig. 2B
).

fluorescence (
Fig. 4A
). The HEK293T tmc_mScarlet-transfected cells were loaded with Fluo-4 AM cell permeant calcium indicator for mechanosensitivity experiments (
Fig. 4B
).

The TMC family has received substantial interest for its potential role in mechano-electrical transduction, particularly in the hair cells of the inner ear of vertebrates (

). Abolishment of mechanosensitivity in the hair cells of TMCknock-out animals is an important finding in support of TMC as a mechanosensitive channel candidate. (

; 

). Hearing loss observed in human mutants of TMC1 and TMC2 supported the hypothesis (

). Observation of similar changes in TMIE protein knockout animals and human mutants, however, has challenged the hypothesis (

; 

; 

). It has been proposed that the mechanical gating process in the hair cells would require a complex structure opposing to that reported in Piezo channels (

). A substantial amount of data conclusively indicates that the TMC protein is among the essential elements of the mechano-electrical transducer complex in the hair cells. A scientific debate nevertheless continues whether the TMC protein can form an independent mechanosensitive channel in the cell membrane (

). The mRNA identified in our work was considered most similar to that of the TMC7 channel subgroup. We scanned through the transcriptome drafts, which we assembled in our model animal, and were not able to find any other transcript for a different subgroup of TMC-like gene family. The search for probable presence of any auxiliary proteins for a channel complex yielded no results. We were unable to find any transcript similar to human TMIE or protocadherin-15, and we hypothesize that the cloned TMC-like protein may function differently.

The TMC protein is present in many phyla, including some invertebrates (
Fig. 2A
). There are a few putative TMC sequences included in shotgun transcriptome assemblies and genome drafts (

). 

Astacus leptodactylus

mRNA is the first crustacean species to be cloned.

Considering the strong similarity in sequence and structure, it is conceivable to propose that the cloned mRNA may code a TMC-like channel protein in the crayfish. It has been reported that TMC functions as a part of a mechanosensitive channel complex in the hair cells. The lack of any transcript, orthologues to TMIE and protocadherin, in the transcriptome draft raises the question that if the cloned channel protein may independently be mechanosensitive. Plasmid transfection and subsequent functional studies did not enable a significant mechanosensitive activity in HEK293T cells. This might be the result of unsuccessful expression of the cloned protein as a functional channel in the surface membrane. It may be interpreted, however, that mScarlet expression indicates only the successful function of the plasmid. A channel complex might be mandatory as it is in the inner ear for a mechanosensitive channel to activate. Further, functional studies indicate that the cloned protein may not possess sodium sensitivity as reported in 

C. elegans

tmc-1 channel. Cell shrinkage by osmotic changes due to increase in the sodium ion concentration might be the cause of the observed rise in the emission (
Fig. 5C
) (see 

). The large variance observed in the recorded emission signals may have limited the discriminative power of the statistical evaluation. The variance might stem from the limited precision of the mechanical stimulation at a single-cell level.
